# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alliance-for-peace-and-freedom
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/adñ-spanish-identity] In October 2018 the political parties La Falange, Spanish Alternative, National Democracy and Falange Española de las JONS announced that they would take part in the 2019 European Parliament election as a coalition named **ADÑ Spanish Identity**.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/adñ-spanish-identity] In 30 of April 2019, the candidature was proclaimed by the Junta Electoral Central, with the name **FE de las JONS-Alternativa Española-La Falange-Democracia Nacional**, with the acronym **ADÑ** (*Ante Todo España*, in English: Above All Spain).
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/adñ-spanish-identity] The coalition takes inspiration in the aesthetic and ideology of other "identitarian" parties in Europe, wanting to take electoral advantage of the Euroscepticism, the suspicion in the PP and the fear to a change in the demographic composition of the country.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/adñ-spanish-identity] The party wants to leave the Eurozone and take back "national sovereignty".
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p01] Lukashenko was born in Kopys, and before embarking on his political career, he worked as the director of a state farm (*sovkhoz*) and served in both the Soviet Border Troops and the Soviet Army.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p01] In 1990, Lukashenko was elected to the Supreme Soviet of the Byelorussian Soviet Socialist Republic.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p01] Following the dissolution of the Soviet Union, he assumed the position of head of the interim anti-corruption committee of the Supreme Council of Belarus.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p01] In 1994, he won the presidency in the country's inaugural presidential election after the adoption of a new constitution.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p01] Lukashenko opposed economic shock therapy during the 1990s post-Soviet transition, maintaining state ownership of key industries in Belarus.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p01] His supporters claim this spared Belarus from recessions as devastating as those in other post-Soviet states, whose political structures devolved into oligarchic crony capitalism.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p01] Lukashenko's maintenance of the socialist economic model is consistent with the retention of Soviet-era symbolism, including the Russian language, coat of arms, and national flag.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p01] These symbols were adopted after a controversial 1995 referendum.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p01] Following the same referendum, Lukashenko acquired increased power, including the authority to dismiss the Supreme Council.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p01] Another referendum in 1996 further facilitated his consolidation of power.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p01] Lukashenko has since presided over an authoritarian government and has commonly been labelled as "Europe's last dictator".
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p01] International monitors have not considered Belarusian elections as free and fair, except for his initial win.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p01] Additionally, the government harshly suppresses opponents and limits media freedom.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p01] Eventually, this has led multiple Western governments to impose sanctions on Lukashenko and other Belarusian officials.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p01] Lukashenko's contested victory in the 2020 presidential election preceded allegations of vote-rigging, amplifying anti-government protests, the largest seen during his rule.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p01] Consequently, the European Union, the United Kingdom, and the United States ceased to recognise Lukashenko as the legitimate president of Belarus following the disputed election.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p01] Lukashenko remained in power, which eventually led to a resumption of partial diplomatic relations.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p01] His re-election in the 2025 presidential election was described as a sham by the opposition and the European parliament.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p01] Lukashenko played a crucial role in creating the Union State, enabling Belarusians and Russians to travel, work, and study unhindered between the two countries.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p01] He also reportedly played a crucial role in brokering a deal to end the Russian Wagner Group rebellion in 2023, allowing some Wagner soldiers to cross the country's border unhindered and settle in Belarus.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p01] Lukashenko was born on 30 August 1954 in the settlement of Kopys in the Vitebsk Region of the Byelorussian Soviet Socialist Republic.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p01] Starting with an interview given in 2009, Lukashenko has said that his actual birthday is 31 August, the same as his son Nikolai's.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p01] This caused some confusion as all official sources had said 30 August 1954 up until then.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p01] An explanation was later given that his mother had entered the hospital on the 30th in labour, but did not give birth until after midnight.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p01] His maternal grandfather, Trokhym Ivanovich Lukashenko, was born near Shostka in the then-Russian Empire, now in the Ukrainian village known today as Sobycheve.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p01] Lukashenko grew up without a father in his childhood, leading him to be taunted by his schoolmates for having an unmarried mother.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p01] Due to this, the origin of his patronymic *Grigorevich* is unknown, and there are varying rumours about the identity of Lukashenko's father.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p01] The most common suggestion is that the man was a Roma passing through the region.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p01] His mother, Ekaterina Trofimovna Lukashenko (1924–2015), had given birth to another son, older than Alexander, who later died on an unknown date.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p01] Ekaterina worked unskilled jobs on a railway, at a construction site, at a flax factory in Orsha, and finally as a milkmaid in Alexandria, a small village in the east of Belarus, close to the Russian border.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p01] Lukashenko went to Alexandria secondary school.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p01] He graduated from the Mogilev Pedagogical Institute (now Mogilev State A.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p01] Kuleshov University) in Mogilev in 1975 after four years of study.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p01] He also completed studies at the Belarusian Agricultural Academy in Horki in 1985.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p01] He served in the Soviet Border Troops from 1975 to 1977, where he was an instructor of the political department of military unit No.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p01] 2187 of the Western Frontier District in Brest, and in the Soviet Army from 1980 to 1982.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p01] In addition, he led an All-Union Leninist Young Communist League (Komsomol) chapter in Mogilev from 1977 to 1978.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p01] While in the Soviet Army, Lukashenko served as a deputy political officer at the 120th Guards Motor Rifle Division, which was based in Minsk.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p01] In 1979, he joined the ranks of the Communist Party of the Soviet Union and the Communist Party of Byelorussia.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p01] After leaving the military, he became the deputy chairman of a collective farm in 1982 and in 1985.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p01] In 1987, he was appointed as the director of the Gorodets state farm in Shklow district, and in early 1988, he was one of the first in the Mogilev Region to introduce a leasing contract to a state farm.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p01] In 1990, Lukashenko was elected a Deputy to the Supreme Soviet of the Byelorussian SSR.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p01] Having acquired a reputation as an eloquent opponent of corruption, Lukashenko was elected in April 1993 to be interim chairman of the anti-corruption committee of the Belarusian parliament.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p01] In late 1993, he accused 70 senior government officials, including Supreme Soviet chairman Stanislav Shushkevich and prime minister Vyacheslav Kebich, of corruption, including embezzlement of state funds for personal purposes.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p01] While the charges ultimately proved to be without merit, Shushkevich resigned his chairmanship due to the embarrassment of this series of events and losing a vote of no-confidence.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p01] He was in that position until July 1994.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] A new Belarusian constitution enacted in early 1994 paved the way for the first democratic presidential election on 23 June and 10 July.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Six candidates stood in the first round, including Lukashenko, who campaigned as an independent on a populist platform.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] In an interview with *The New York Times*, he declared, "I am neither with the leftists nor the rightists.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] But with the people against those who rob and deceive them." Stanislav Shushkevich and Vyacheslav Kebich also ran, with the latter regarded as the clear favourite.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Lukashenko won 45.1% of the vote while Kebich received 17.4%, Zianon Pazniak received 12.9% and Shushkevich, along with two other candidates, received less than 10% of the cast votes.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Lukashenko won the second round of the election on 10 July with 80.1% of the vote.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] The presidential inauguration was held in the halls of the Government House on 20 July 1994, exactly ten days after the election, during a special meeting of the parliament, the Supreme Council.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Shortly after his inauguration, he addressed the State Duma of the Russian Federation in Moscow, proposing a new Union of Slavic states, which would culminate in the creation of the Union of Russia and Belarus in 1999.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] In February 1995, Lukashenko announced his intention to hold a referendum.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] For the young democratic republic, this raised the controversial issue of the Russification of Belarus.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Lukashenko said he would press ahead with the referendum regardless of opposition in the Supreme Council and threatened to suspend its activities if it did not agree to hold the referendum.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] On 11 April 1995, a vote was held in parliament on calling a referendum on four issues proposed by Lukashenko: 1) granting Russian the status of a state language, 2) changing state symbols, 3) on economic integration with Russia, and 4) on giving the president the right to dissolve parliament.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] The deputies rejected all the issues, except for that which regarded economic integration with Russia.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] It is unclear whether the president had legal power to call referendums independently, and if so, whether they would be binding.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Lukashenko stated that the referendum would be held despite the rejection by the deputies.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] At night, under the pretext of a bomb threat, unidentified law enforcement personnel attacked and forcibly expelled the deputies.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Lukashenko stated that he personally ordered the evacuation for security purposes.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] The Supreme Council agreed to hold the referendum on 13 April, and in May 1995, Belarusian authorities held a referendum on the four issues.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] The Parliamentary Assembly of the Organisation for Security and Co-operation in Europe found neither the referendum nor the 1995 Belarusian parliamentary election, which took place in the same month, to have met the minimal requirements for free and fair elections.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] In the summer of 1996, deputies of the 199-member Belarusian parliament signed a petition to impeach Lukashenko on charges of violating the Constitution.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Shortly after that, a referendum was held on 24 November 1996 in which four questions were offered by Lukashenko and three offered by a group of Parliament members.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] The questions ranged from social issues, including changing the country's Independence Day to 3 July (the date of the liberation of Minsk from Nazi forces in 1944) and the abolition of the death penalty, to the national constitution.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] As a result of the referendum, the constitution that was amended by Lukashenko was accepted, while the one amended by the Supreme Council was voided.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] On 25 November, it was announced that 70.5% of voters, of an 84% turnout, had approved the amended constitution.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] The US and the EU, however, refused to accept the referendum's legitimacy.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] After the referendum, Lukashenko convened a new parliamentary assembly from those members of the parliament who were loyal to him.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] After between ten and twelve deputies withdrew their signatures from the impeachment petition, only about forty deputies of the old parliament were left, and the Supreme Council was dismissed by Lukashenko.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Nevertheless, international organisations and most Western countries refuse to recognise the current parliament because of the (unjust and illegal) manner in which it was formed.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Lukashenko was elected chairman of the Belarusian Olympic Committee in 1997.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] At the start of 1998, the Central Bank of Russia suspended trading of the Belarusian ruble, which led to a collapse in the value of the currency.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Lukashenko responded by taking control of the National Bank of the Republic of Belarus, sacking the entire bank leadership, and blaming the West for the currency's free-fall.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Lukashenko blamed foreign governments for conspiring against him and, in April 1998, expelled ambassadors from the Drazdy complex near Minsk and moved them to another building.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] The Drazdy conflict caused an international outcry and resulted in a travel ban on Lukashenko from both the EU and the US.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Although the ambassadors eventually returned after the controversy died down, Lukashenko stepped up his rhetorical attacks against the West.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] He stated that Western governments were trying to undermine Belarus at all levels, even sports, during the 1998 Winter Olympics in Nagano, Japan.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Upon the outbreak of the Kosovo War in 1999, Lukashenko suggested to Yugoslav President Slobodan Milošević that Yugoslavia join the Union of Russia and Belarus.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Under the original constitution, Lukashenko should have been up for reelection in 1999.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] However, the 1996 referendum extended Lukashenko's term for two additional years.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] In the 9 September 2001 election, Lukashenko faced Vladimir Goncharik and Sergei Gaidukevich.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] During the campaign, Lukashenko promised to raise the standards of farming and social benefits as well as increase Belarus's industrial output.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Lukashenko won in the first round with 75.65% of the vote.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] The Organisation for Security and Co-operation in Europe (OSCE) said the election process "failed to meet international standards".
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Following the 2003 invasion of Iraq, US intelligence agencies reported that aides of Saddam Hussein managed to acquire Belarusian passports while in Syria, but that it was unlikely that Belarus would offer a safe haven for Saddam and his two sons.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] This action, along with arms deals with Iraq and Iran, prompted Western governments to take a tougher stance against Lukashenko.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] The US was particularly angered by the arms sales, and US political leaders increasingly began to refer to Belarus as "Europe's last dictatorship".
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] The EU was concerned for the security of its gas supplies from Russia, which are piped through Belarus, and took an active interest in Belarusian affairs.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] With the accession of Poland, Latvia, and Lithuania, the EU's border with Belarus has grown to more than 1000 kilometers.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] During a televised address to the nation on 7 September 2004, Lukashenko announced plans for a referendum to eliminate presidential term limits.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] This was held on 17 October 2004, the same day as parliamentary elections, and, according to official results, was approved by 79.42% of voters.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Previously, Lukashenko had been limited to two terms and thus would have been constitutionally required to step down after the presidential elections in 2006.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Opposition groups, the OSCE, the European Union, and the US State Department stated that the vote fell short of international standards.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Belarus grew economically under Lukashenko, but much of this growth was due to Russian crude oil, which was imported at below-market prices, refined, and sold to other European countries at a profit.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] After Lukashenko confirmed he was running for re-election in 2005, opposition groups began to seek a single candidate.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] On 16 October 2005, on the Day of Solidarity with Belarus, the political groups Zubr and Third Way Belarus encouraged all opposition parties to rally behind one candidate to oppose Lukashenko in the 2006 election.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Their chosen candidate was Alexander Milinkevich.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Lukashenko reacted by saying that anyone going to opposition protests would have their necks wrung "as one might a duck".
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] On 19 March 2006, exit polls showed Lukashenko winning a third term in a landslide, amid opposition reports of vote-rigging and fear of violence.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] The Belarusian Republican Youth Union gave Lukashenko 84.2% and Milinkevich 3.1%.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Gallup, Inc., an internationally renowned US analytics company, noted that the Belarusian Republican Youth Union is a government-controlled organisation and released the exit poll results before noon on election day, even though voting stations did not close until 20:00.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Belarusian authorities vowed to prevent any large-scale demonstrations following the election (such as those that marked the Orange Revolution in Ukraine).
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Despite their efforts, the opposition had the largest number of demonstrators in years, with nightly protests in Minsk continuing for a number of days after the election.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] The largest protest occurred on election night; reporters for the Associated Press estimated that approximately 10,000 people turned out.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Election observers from the Russia-led Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS) and the Organisation for Security and Co-operation in Europe (OSCE) differed on the Belarusian election.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Although he had won 93.5% of the vote, he said, he had directed the government to announce a result of 86%.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Some Russian nationalists, such as Dmitry Rogozin and the Movement Against Illegal Immigration, stated that they would like to see Lukashenko become President of Russia in 2008.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Lukashenko responded that he would not run for the Russian presidency, but that if his health was still good, he might run for reelection in 2011.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] In September 2008, parliamentary elections were held.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Lukashenko had allowed some opposition candidates to stand, though in the official results, opposition members failed to get any of the 110 available seats.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] OSCE observers described the vote as "flawed", including "several cases of deliberate falsification of results".
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Opposition members and supporters demonstrated in protest.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] According to the Nizhny Novgorod-based CIS election observation mission, the findings of which are often dismissed by the West, the elections in Belarus conformed to international standards.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Lukashenko later commented that the opposition in Belarus was financed by foreign countries and was not needed.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] In April 2009, he held talks with Pope Benedict XVI in the Vatican, Lukashenko's first visit to Western Europe after a travel ban on him a decade earlier.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Later, Lukashenko received the nickname "potato führer" from his detractors.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Lukashenko was one of ten candidates registered for the presidential election held in Belarus on 19 December 2010.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Though originally envisaged for 2011, an earlier date was approved "to ensure the maximum participation of citizens in the electoral campaign and to set the most convenient time for the voters." The run-up to the campaign was marked by a series of Russian media attacks on Lukashenko.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] The Central Election Committee said that all nine opposition figures were likely to receive less than half the vote total that Lukashenko would receive.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Though opposition figures alleged intimidation and that "dirty tricks" were being played, the election was seen as comparatively open as a result of the desire to improve relations with both Europe and the US.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] On election day, two presidential candidates were seriously beaten by police in different opposition rallies.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] On the night of the election, opposition protesters chanting "Out!", "Long live Belarus!" and other similar slogans attempted to storm the building of the government of Belarus, smashing windows and doors before riot police were able to push them back.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] The number of protesters was reported by major news media as being around or above 10,000 people.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] At least seven of the opposition presidential candidates were arrested.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Several of the opposition candidates, along with their supporters and members of the media, were arrested.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Many were sent to prison, often on charges of organising a mass disturbance.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Examples include Andrei Sannikov, Alexander Otroschenkov, Ales Michalevic, Mikola Statkevich, and Uladzimir Nyaklyayew.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Sannikov's wife, journalist Irina Khalip, was put under house arrest.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Yaraslau Ramanchuk's party leader, Anatoly Lebedko, was also arrested.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] The CEC said that Lukashenko won 79.65% of the vote (he gained 5,130,557 votes) with 90.65% of the electorate voting.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] The OSCE categorised the elections as "flawed," while the CIS mission observers approved the results as legitimate.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] However, the OSCE also stated that some improvements were made in the run-up to the election, including the candidates' use of television debates and the ability to deliver their messages unhindered.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] EU ambassadors boycotted Lukashenko's inauguration ceremony of 22 January 2011, and only thirty-two foreign diplomats attended.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] During this ceremony, Lukashenko defended the legitimacy of his re-election and vowed that Belarus would never have its own version of the 2004 Orange Revolution in Ukraine or Georgia's 2003 Rose Revolution.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Effective 31 January 2011, the EU renewed a travel ban, prohibiting Lukashenko and 156 of his associates from traveling to EU member countries, as a result of the crackdown on opposition supporters.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Lukashenko was supportive of China's Belt and Road Initiative global infrastructure development strategy, and the inception in 2012 of the associated low-tax China–Belarus Industrial Park near Minsk National Airport, planned to grow to 112 square kilometres (43 sq mi) by the 2060s.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] On 11 October 2015, Lukashenko was elected for his fifth term as the president of Belarus.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Just over three weeks later, he was inaugurated in the Independence Palace in the presence of attendees such as former president of Ukraine Leonid Kuchma, Chairman of the Russian Communist Party Gennady Zyuganov, and Belarusian biathlete Darya Domracheva.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] In mid-September 2017, Lukashenko oversaw the advancement of joint Russian and Belarusian military relations during the military drills that were part of the Zapad 2017 exercise.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] In August 2018, Lukashenko fired his prime minister, Andrei Kobyakov, and several other officials due to a corruption scandal.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Eventually, Sergei Rumas was appointed prime minister as successor to Kobyakov.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] In May 2017, Lukashenko signed a decree on the Foundation of the Directorate of the 2019 European Games in Minsk.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] In April 2019, Lukashenko announced that the games were on budget and on time, and eventually, he opened the 2nd edition of the event on 21 June.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Between 1–3 July 2019, he oversaw the country's celebrations of the 75th anniversary of the Minsk Offensive, which culminated in an evening military parade of the Armed Forces of Belarus on the last day, which is the country's Independence Day.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] In August 2019, Lukashenko met with former Kyrgyz president Kurmanbek Bakiyev, who has lived in exile in Minsk since 2010, in the Palace of Independence to mark Bakiyev's 70th birthday, which he had marked several days earlier.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] During the visit, he met with President Alexander Van der Bellen, Chancellor Brigitte Bierlein, and National Council President Wolfgang Sobotka.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] He also paid his respects at the Soviet War Memorial at the Schwarzenbergplatz.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] During the course of the COVID-19 pandemic, he undertook two working visits to Russia, one of the few European leaders to undertake foreign visits during the pandemic.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] He also received Hungarian prime minister Viktor Orbán on the latter's state visit to Minsk.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] During this visit, Orbán called for an end to EU sanctions on Belarus.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] His first visit to Russia was to attend the rescheduled Moscow Victory Day Parade on Red Square together with his son.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] On 9 August 2020, according to the preliminary count, Lukashenko was re-elected for his sixth term as the president of Belarus.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] US Secretary of State Mike Pompeo warned that the election was "not free [or] fair".
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Mass protests erupted across Belarus following the 2020 Belarusian presidential election, which was marred by allegations of widespread electoral fraud.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Subsequently, opposition presidential candidate Sviatlana Tsikhanouskaya claimed she had received between 60 and 70% of the vote and formed a Coordination Council to facilitate the peaceful and orderly transfer of power in Belarus.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] On 15 August 2020, Lithuanian foreign minister Linas Linkevičius referred to Lukashenko as the "former president" of Belarus.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] It was reported that President Lukashenko's authorities asked Kremlin representatives about the possibility of Lukashenko escaping to Russia.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Furthermore, it was reported that Russia admits that Lukashenko's resignation from the post of head of state is likely.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] On 17 August 2020, the members of the European Parliament issued a joint statement which stated that they do not recognise Alexander Lukashenko as the president of Belarus, considering him to be *persona non grata* in the European Union.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] In an interview on 22 August, Josep Borrell explicitly stated that the European Union does not recognise Lukashenko as the legitimate president of Belarus in the same manner that it does not recognise Nicolás Maduro as the legitimate president of Venezuela.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] On 23 August 2020, footage emerged showing Lukashenko at the Independence Palace in Minsk.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] In the first two videos, he is seen walking near a helicopter, wearing a bulletproof vest and holding an AKS-74U assault rifle, and then walking around the palace grounds.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] In the latter footage, Lukashenko was heard to say, "Leave me alone," and "There is no one left there, right?" His 15-year-old son, Nikolai, was seen with him dressed in military uniform and holding a gun.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] In a third video, he is seen surveying protestors from a helicopter and is heard saying "How the rats ran away" in an apparent reference to the protesters.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] In a fourth video, Lukashenko was seen removing the former flag of Belarus from a flower bed, waving at security personnel, and, in reference to protesters, saying, "We will deal with them." On 30 August, the Independence Palace became again a scene of protests.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] When questioned about the whereabouts of Alexander Lukashenko on this day, his publicity team released an undated photograph of him walking around the grounds of the Independence Palace holding a gun.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] On 23 September 2020, Lukashenko was secretly inaugurated president for a sixth term in a ceremony at the Palace of Independence attended by an invited group of 700 guests.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] On 27 November 2020, Lukashenko announced that he would resign once Belarus' new constitution was adopted.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] In December, the executive board of the International Olympic Committee (IOC) decided to exclude until further notice all members of the Belarusian Olympic Committee from all IOC events, specifically targeting Lukashenko who was elected as its chairman in 1997.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] On 17 April 2021, Russia's FSB security service exposed an alleged military coup and assassination attempt of Lukashenko.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Russia also stated that it prevented Lukashenko's murder.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Two suspects, who were detained at Lukashenko's request, were Alyaksandr Feduta and Yuras Zyankovich.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Both are critics of Lukashenko, with the latter being a dual US-Belarusian citizen, despite Belarus not recognising dual citizenship.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] On 24 April 2021, Lukashenko announced that he would sign a decree to amend emergency transfer of power.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] "I will sign a decree about how the power in Belarus will be set up.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] If the President is shot the security council will get the power." Lukashenko is the head of the Security Council himself; however, his eldest son, Victor Lukashenko, is regarded as its informal leader.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] This move was seen to empower his son, to be in the perfect position to succeed him in the next elections.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Under current law, the prime minister assumes the presidential powers if the presidency becomes vacant, but Lukashenko said that the prime minister will only become the nominal leader and all decisions would be taken by the 20-person security council, by secret ballot.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] On 5 May 2021, Belarusians in Germany filed a legal complaint against Lukashenko for 'state torture' and 'crimes against humanity.' If he enters Germany he risks trial or if convicted and enters Germany faces punishment given by court.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Lukashenko responded that Germany was not in a position to criticise him, referring to the German Government as the "Heirs of Fascism".
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] At the same time, he said that he will not resign, a reversal from his statement in November, but said he will call early presidential elections if and only if the United States does so as well.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] On 24 June 2023, Lukashenko said that with Vladimir Putin's agreement, he had negotiated with Yevgeny Prigozhin to end the Wagner Group rebellion.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Lukashenko told Prigozhin that they would be squashed like bugs if they tried to enter Belarus by force and warned that Putin would never agree to remove top generals, including Defense minister Sergei Shoigu.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] He promised to accommodate Wagner's troops in Belarus.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] He claimed that Putin desired to destroy the Wagner Group after the mutiny, and that he had prevented Putin from carrying out the obliteration of the group.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Lukashenko's rule in the crisis raised his clout internationally.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] On 25 March 2023, Putin announced plans to install Russian tactical nuclear weapons in Belarus.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] On 27 September 2024, Lukashenko publicly warned that Belarus would use nuclear weapons if attacked by the West.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Lukashenko was re-elected in the 2025 Belarusian presidential election on 26 January, with official results showing that he had won around 88% of the vote.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] He was inaugurated for his seventh term as president on 25 March.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] In April 2025, after meeting with Pakistani Prime Minister Shehbaz Sharif in Minsk, Lukashenko announced a plan to open Belarus to 150,000 migrant workers from Pakistan.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Lukashenko's migration plans have raised concerns in neighboring Poland and among the Belarusian public.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] In August 2025, Lukashenko announced that he was "not planning" to seek another term at the next election and also dismissed speculations of grooming his son, Nikolai, to succeed him as president.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] The political system created by Lukashenko has become colloquially known as "Lukashism" or "Lukashenkoism".
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Lukashenko promotes himself as a "man of the people." Lukashenko wanted to rebuild Belarus when he took office; the economy was in free-fall due to declining industry and lack of demand for Belarusian goods.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Lukashenko kept many industries under the control of the government.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] With the ascent to power of Lukashenko in 1994, the Russification policy of the Russian Imperial and Soviet era was renewed.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] In 2006, Lukashenko said that people who speak Belarusian language cannot do anything, because nothing great can be expressed in the Belarusian language as it is a poor language, whereas there are only two great languages in the world: Russian and English.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Since the November 1996 referendum, Lukashenko has effectively held all governing power in the nation.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Under the Constitution, if the House of Representatives rejects his choice for prime minister twice, he has the right to dissolve it.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] His decrees have greater weight than ordinary legislation.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] He also has near-absolute control over government spending; parliament can only increase or decrease spending with his permission.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] However, the legislature is dominated by his supporters in any event, and there is no substantive opposition to presidential decisions.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Indeed, every seat in the lower house has been held by pro-Lukashenko MPs for all but one term since 2004.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] He also appoints eight members of the upper house, the Council of the Republic, as well as nearly all judges.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Lukashenko's early economic policies aimed to prevent issues that have occurred in other post-Soviet states, such as the establishment of oligarchic structures and mass unemployment.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] The unemployment rate for the country at the end of 2011 was at 0.6% of the population (of 6.86 million eligible workers), a decrease from 1995, when unemployment was 2.9% with a working-eligible population of 5.24 million.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] One major economic issue Lukashenko has faced throughout his presidency has been the value of the Belarusian ruble.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] For a time it was pegged to major foreign currencies, such as the euro, US dollar and the Russian ruble in order to maintain its stability.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Yet, the currency has experienced several periods of devaluation.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] A major devaluation took place in 2011 after the government announced that average salaries would increase to US$500.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] According to the World Bank, the 2011 devaluation was the largest on record for the past twenty years.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Belarus also had to seek a bailout from international sources and, although it has received loans from China, other loans, including those from the IMF, have been dependent on how Belarus reforms its economy.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Some critics of Lukashenko, including the opposition group Zubr, use the term *Lukashism* to refer to the political and economic system Lukashenko has implemented in Belarus.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] The term is also used more broadly to refer to an authoritarian ideology based on a cult of personality and nostalgia for Soviet times among certain groups in Belarus.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] The US Congress sought to aid the opposition groups by passing the Belarus Democracy Act of 2004 to introduce sanctions against Lukashenko's government and provide financial and other support to the opposition.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Lukashenko supporters argue that his rule spared Belarus the turmoil that beset many other former Soviet countries.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Lukashenko commented on the criticism of him by saying: "I've been hearing these accusations for over 10 years and we have got used to it.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] I want to come from the premise that the elections in Belarus are held for ourselves.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] During the COVID-19 pandemic, Lukashenko stated that concerns about the pandemic were a "frenzy and a psychosis" and that working the tractors, drinking vodka and going to saunas could prevent people from infection from the virus.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] No one is talking about the virus", Lukashenko said on 16 March 2020.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] He also said: "I don't drink, but recently I've been saying that people should not only wash their hands with vodka, but also poison the virus with it.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] You should drink the equivalent of 40–50 milliliters of rectified spirit daily", but he advised against doing so while at work.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Lukashenko described these comments as a joke.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] By early May, Belarus was reported to have 15,000 diagnosed cases, one of the highest per capita rates of infection in Eastern Europe.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] On 28 July 2020, Lukashenko announced he had asymptomatic COVID-19.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Neither the Presidential Administration nor the country's health service have commented on this statement.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] On 12 August 2021, Lukashenko stated that he was strongly opposed to making vaccination mandatory.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] "There will be no mandatory vaccination in Belarus.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] If a person wants to be vaccinated it is good, if not, let it be".
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] On 1 September 2020, the Office of the United Nations High Commissioner for Human Rights (OHCHR) declared that its experts received reports of 450 documented cases of torture and ill-treatment of people who were arrested during the protests following the presidential election.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] The experts also received reports of violence against women and children, including sexual abuse and rape with rubber batons.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] According to the OHCHR, both male and female detainees were subjected to rape and other forms of sexual and gender-based violence.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Medical records reviewed by OHCHR indicate lesions and other injuries to the male genitalia associated with forcible twisting and rape.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Psychological violence, including threats of rape, was also used against detainees.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] At least three detainees suffered injuries indicative of sexual violence in Okrestino prison in Minsk or on the way there.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] The victims were hospitalised with intramuscular bleeding of the rectum, anal fissure and bleeding, and damage to the mucous membrane of the rectum.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] In an interview from September 2020 Lukashenko claimed that detainees faked their bruises, saying, "Some of the girls there had their butts painted in blue".
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] In November 2021, however, Lukashenko confirmed in an interview to the BBC that people were beaten in Okrestino, saying: "OK, OK, I admit it, I admit it.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] People were beaten in the Okrestina Detention Centre.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] In January 2021, an audio recording was released in which the commander of internal troops and deputy interior minister of Belarus Mikalai Karpiankou tells security forces that they can cripple, maim and kill protesters in order to make them understand their actions.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] This, he says, is justified because anyone who takes to the streets is participating in a kind of guerrilla warfare.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] In addition, he discussed the establishment of camps, surrounded by barbed wire, where protesters will be detained until the situation calms down.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] A spokeswoman for the Interior Ministry stamped the audio file as a fake.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] However, a phonoscopic examination of the audio recording confirmed that the voice on the recording belongs to Karpiankou.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] The Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe expressed its concern about the remarks.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] According to Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty, such a camp was indeed used near the town of Slutsk in the days from 13 to 15 August 2020.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Many of those detained there are said to have been brought from the Okrestina prison in Minsk.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] In March 2023, Lukashenko signed a law which allows to use capital punishment against officials and soldiers convicted of high treason.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] In 1999 opposition leaders Yury Zacharanka and Viktar Hanchar together with his business associate Anatol Krasouski disappeared.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] The investigation of the disappearance of journalist Dzmitry Zavadski in 2000 has also yielded no results.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Copies of a report by the Parliamentary Assembly of the Council of Europe, which linked senior Belarusian officials to the cases of disappearances, were confiscated.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] On 4 January 2021, the EU Observer reported that new evidence, including documents and audio recordings, provide that Belarusian secret services planned to murder dissidents abroad.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] An audio file, allegedly being a recording from a bugged meeting in 2012, reveals Vadim Zaitsev, the KGB chairman at the time, discussing the murder plot with two officers from the KGB's Alpha Group, an elite counter-terrorism unit.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Translated from Russian, one of the voices in the recording says, "We should be working with Sheremet, who is a massive pain in the arse [inaudible].
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] We'll plant [a bomb] and so on and this fucking rat will be taken down in fucking pieces, legs in one direction, arms in the other direction.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] If everything [looks like] natural causes, it won't get into people's minds the same way." In addition to planting a bomb, they also discuss poisoning Sheremet.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] On 23 May 2021, Lukashenko personally ordered Ryanair Flight 4978 en route from Athens to Vilnius, carrying the opposition journalist Roman Protasevich, to land in Belarus.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] The flight was forced to land at Minsk International Airport shortly before it reached the Lithuanian border after Belarusian air traffic control conveyed a report of explosives on board the plane.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] The flight was escorted by a Belarusian Air Force MiG-29 fighter jet.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Belarusian authorities said no explosives were found and arrested Protasevich, who was placed in a list of "individuals involved in terrorist activity" the previous year for his role in the anti-government protests and incitement to public disorder.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] The move was condemned by opposition figures, with Tsikhanouskaya saying that Protasevich "faces the death penalty" in Belarus.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] In the 1990s, Lukashenko and the then-Russian president Boris Yeltsin envisaged the formation of a Union State.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Yeltsin suffered from poor health and alcoholism, which induced Lukashenko into thinking that he would lead both states.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] But after Yeltsin anointed Putin as his successor, Lukashenko stalled the merger.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Lukashenko's relationship with Russia, once his powerful ally and vocal supporter, has significantly deteriorated.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] The run-up to the 2010 Belarusian presidential election was marked by a series of Russian media attacks on Lukashenko.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Throughout July state-controlled channel NTV broadcast a multi-part documentary entitled "The Godfather" highlighting the suspicious disappearance of the opposition leaders Yury Zacharanka and Viktar Hanchar, businessman Anatol Krasouski and journalist Dzmitry Zavadski during the late 1990s.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Lukashenko called the media attack "dirty propaganda".
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Despite a historically good relationship with Russia, tensions between Lukashenko and the Russian government started showing in 2020.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] On 24 January 2020, Lukashenko publicly accused Russian president Vladimir Putin of trying to make Belarus a part of Russia.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] This led to Russia cutting economic subsidies for Belarus.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] In July 2020, the relationship between Belarus and Russia was described as "strained" after 33 Russian military contractors were arrested in Minsk.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] On 5 August 2020, Russia's security chief Dmitry Medvedev warned Belarus to release the contractors.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Lukashenko also claimed Russia was lying about its attempts to use the Wagner Group to influence the upcoming election.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] On 11 November 2021, Lukashenko raised the possibility of interrupting the Yamal–Europe pipeline carrying Russian gas to the European Union if the bloc imposes further sanctions on Belarus.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Putin said that Lukashenko had not consulted him before raising the possibility of stopping gas deliveries coming from Russia to the EU via a pipeline through Belarus, adding that such a move would risk harming ties between Belarus and Russia.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] In February 2022, Lukashenko permitted Russian forces to stage part of the invasion of Ukraine from Belarusian territory.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Commenting on the war in Ukraine Lukashenko has said that he didn't expect the conflict “drag on this way.” In June 2023, Lukashenko claimed that "the only mistake we made’ was not finishing off Ukraine with Russia in 2014".
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] In August 2024, Lukashenko urged both Russia and Ukraine to start peace negotiations, saying in an interview with Russian state television: "Neither the Ukrainian people, nor the Russians, nor the Belarusians need it.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] It’s them in the West, who need [the war]." He accused the West of supporting Ukraine's incursion into the Kursk region.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Lukashenko's relationship with the EU has been strained, in part by choice and in part by his policies towards domestic opponents.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Lukashenko's repression of opponents caused him to be called "Europe's last dictator" and resulted in the EU imposing visa sanctions on him and a range of Belarusian officials.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] At times, the EU has lifted sanctions as a way to encourage dialogue or gain concessions from Lukashenko.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Since the EU adopted this policy of "change through engagement", it has supported economic and political reforms to help integrate the Belarusian state.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] After the EU sanctioned Belarus for its crackdown against the 2020 mass protests, Lukashenko advertised Belarus as an entry point for migrants to reach the EU, resulting in the Belarus–European Union border crisis.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] In March 2003, Lukashenko said that Belarus unanimously condemned the US-led Iraq War.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] On 29 August 2019, John Bolton, then National Security Advisor of the United States, was received by Lukashenko during his visit to Minsk, which was the first of its kind in 18 years.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] On 1 March 2023, Lukashenko met Chinese leader Xi Jinping in Beijing, which produced a range of cooperation documents on industry, trade, agricultural, and other matters.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Following the 2014 Syrian presidential election, President Lukashenko congratulated President Bashar al-Assad.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Belarus condemned the NATO-led military intervention in Libya, and the foreign ministry stated that "the missile strikes and bombings on the territory of Libya go beyond Resolution 1973 of the UN Security Council and are in breach of its principal goal, ensuring safety of the civilian population.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] The Republic of Belarus calls on the states involved with the military operation to cease, with immediate effect, the military operations which lead to human casualties.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] The settlement of the conflict is an internal affair of Libya and should be carried out by the Libyan people alone without military intervention from outside." They did not recognise the National Transitional Council.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Upon hearing the news regarding the death of Libyan leader Muammar Gaddafi, Alexander Lukashenko said that "aggression has been committed, and the country's leadership, not only Muammar Gaddafi, has been killed.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Well, if they had shot him in a battle, it's one thing, but they humiliated and tormented him, they shot at him, they violated him when he was wounded, they twisted his neck and arms, and then they tortured him to death.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] It's worse than the Nazis once did." He also condemned the current situation of Libya and was critical regarding the future of the country.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] His policies have been praised by some other world leaders.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] In response to a question about Belarus's domestic policies, President Hugo Chávez of Venezuela said "We see here a model social state like the one we are beginning to create." In 2015, Lukashenko sought to improve trade relations between Belarus and Latin America.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] In March 2022, Australia sanctioned Lukashenko for giving "strategic support to Russia and its military forces" in the Russian invasion of Ukraine.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Also in 2022, he was blacklisted by New Zealand and Japan on the same grounds.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] In February 2026, Ukraine joined the sanctions against Alexander Lukashenko.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] In September 2023, Lukashenko, reacting to the 2023 North Korea–Russia summit, proposed a three-way cooperation pact with Russia and North Korea.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] In March 2026, Lukashenko visited North Korea, marking his first state visit to North Korea, as well as the first visit to the country by a Belarusian President.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] He was greeted by North Korean Vice Premier Kim Tok-hun at the Pyongyang International Airport.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] Lukashenko visited the Kumsusan Palace of the Sun, where he laid flowers at the resting place of former leaders Kim Il Sung and Kim Jong Il.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] He then met with North Korean leader Kim Jong Un, and took part in a ceremony at Kim Il Sung Square.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p02] During the meeting, the two sides signed a friendship and cooperation treaty.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p03] Lukashenko has made several controversial statements during his presidency which have been regarded as antisemitic, homophobic and misogynistic.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p03] In 1995, Lukashenko made a remark in which he named Adolf Hitler as a role model for his presidential system in Belarus: "The history of Germany is a copy of the history of Belarus.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p03] Germany was raised from ruins thanks to firm authority and not everything connected with that well-known figure Hitler was bad.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p03] German order evolved over the centuries and attained its peak under Hitler.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p03] This corresponds with our understanding of a presidential republic and the role of a president in it." Lukashenko refused to take the quote back, but stated that the consequences of Hitler's leadership style in foreign policy had been bad.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p03] In October 2007, Lukashenko was accused of making antisemitic comments; addressing the "miserable state of the city of Babruysk" on a live broadcast on state radio, he stated: "This is a Jewish city, and the Jews are not concerned for the place they live in.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p03] They have turned Babruysk into a pigsty.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p03] After some of the initial candidates for the 2020 Belarusian presidential election were imprisoned, three women involved with the candidates, led by Sviatlana Tsikhanouskaya emerged as leading opposition against him and contested the results of the election.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p03] In July 2021, Lukashenko was accused of making antisemitic comments during his Independence Day speech to the armed forces; saying "the Jews managed to force the world to remember the Holocaust.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p03] The entire world grovels before them and gives in to them.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p03] They are afraid to say a single word out of place" and adding "We are tolerant and likeable.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p03] We left things alone until it got to the point where others started attacking us and the memory of our efforts." The Israeli government said the comments were "unacceptable" and summoned the chargé d'affaires at the Belarus embassy in Israel.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p03] In June 2026, in an interview with Al Arabiya, Lukashenko described the Gaza war as a "holocaust" and referenced a "Jewish lobby" that "got the United States involved" in the Iran war.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p03] The statements were condemned by Israeli officials as "revival of vile, outdated antisemitic conspiracies" and "deeply disturbing".
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p03] Independent polling is tightly restricted in Belarus.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p03] Surveys are monopolised by the government, which either does not publish its surveys or uses them for propagandistic purposes.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p03] According to a leaked internal poll, a third of the population had trust in Lukashenko.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p03] The last credible public poll in Belarus was a 2016 poll showing approximately 30% approval for Lukashenko.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p03] Lukashenko is referred to as "Batska" (бацька, "father") by his supporters.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p03] During the 2020–21 Belarusian protests, opponents of Lukashenko began to refer to him as "Sasha 3%" on the basis that they believed that he was only supported by three percent of the Belarusian population.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p03] The term has subsequently become a popular meme within the Belarusian opposition appearing on T-shirts and posters.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p03] Lukashenko has also been referred to as "Tarakanishche" ("Cockroach") by his opponents in reference to the poem "The Monster Cockroach", in which a moustached cockroach inflicts a reign of terror on the other animals before being eaten by a sparrow.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p03] A film produced by Nexta, a Belarusian media service based in Poland, accuses Lukashenko of misappropriating EU funds on residences and automobiles.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p03] The film was uploaded to Telegram and YouTube, where it had over 6 million views.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p03] Lukashenko did not comment on the film directly, but on a factory visit in March 2021 claimed that opponents were creating a fake story to destabilise the country.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p03] Lukashenko married Galina Zhelnerovich, his high school sweetheart, in 1975.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p03] Later that year, his oldest son, Viktor, was born.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p03] Their second son, Dmitry, was born in 1980.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p03] Galina lives separately in a house in the village Shklow.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p03] Though they are still legally married, Galina Lukashenko has been estranged from her husband since shortly after he became president.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p03] In a 2014 interview, Lukashenko said that they had not lived together for 30 years and the only reason they had not divorced was that he did not want to traumatise his adult sons.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p03] Lukashenko has been seen on public occasions with various women; when asked about this in the same 2014 interview he explained that he did not want to sit with an official with a "sour face", preferring "My son on one side, and a girl on the other".
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p03] Lukashenko fathered a son, Nikolai, who was born in 2004.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p03] Though never confirmed by the government, it is widely believed that Nikolai's mother is Irina Abelskaya—the two had an extramarital affair when she was Lukashenko's personal doctor.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p03] There has never been any public statement about who Nikolai's mother is; Nikolai was raised solely by his father.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p03] It has been reported by Western observers and media that Nikolai, nicknamed "Kolya", is being groomed as Lukashenko's successor.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p03] According to Belarusian state media, these speculations were dismissed by Lukashenko, who also denied that he would remain in office for a further thirty years—the time Nikolai will become eligible to stand for election and succeed him.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p03] Lukashenko has a pet dog, a spitz named Umka.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p03] Lukashenko used to play football, but stopped playing during his presidency.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p03] His two elder sons also play ice hockey, sometimes alongside their father.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p03] Lukashenko started training in cross-country running as a child, and in the 2000s still competed at the national level.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p03] He is a keen skier and ice hockey forward.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p03] In an interview he said that he plays ice hockey three times a week.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p03] He has established the Belarus President's team, an amateur team which he sometimes plays for.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p03] Numerous ice rinks intended to enable competitive ice hockey games to be played, have been built all over Belarus at Lukashenko's behest.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p03] Lukashenko was instrumental in getting the 2014 IIHF World Championship in ice hockey to be hosted by Belarus which was considered controversial due to Lukashenko's repressive regime.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p03] Belarus was supposed to host the 2021 IIHF World Championship in May 2021, but that was cancelled after international condemnation and threats by sponsors to withdraw.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p03] Lukashenko describes himself as an "Orthodox atheist" and has said that he believes that a president should be a conservative person and avoid using modern electronic technology such as a tablet or smartphone.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p03] He used to play the bayan, a musical instrument similar to an accordion.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p03] In this name that follows East Slavic naming customs, the patronymic is *Grigoryevich* and the family name is *Lukashenko*.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p03] Belarusian: Аляксандр Рыгоравіч Лукашэнка, IPA: [alʲækˈsand(ɐ)r rɨˈɣɔravʲit͡ʂ lukaˈʂɛnka].
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alexander-lukashenko-p03] In English, both transliterations from Belarusian and Russian are used, and his first name is often anglicised to *Alexander*.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe] The **Alliance for Direct Democracy in Europe**, abbreviated to **ADDE**, was a European political party founded in 2014.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe] It was composed of parties belonging to the Europe of Freedom and Direct Democracy (EFDD) group in the European Parliament (EP).
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe] The dominant national party in the ADDE was the UK Independence Party (UKIP), providing 21 of the party's 27 members of the European Parliament (MEPs) elected in 2014.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe] A further three UKIP MEPs chose not to participate in the ADDE.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe] In 2015, the ADDE was recognised by the European Parliament and its grant maximum from the EP was set at €1,241,725, with an additional €730,053 for its affiliated political foundation, the *Initiative for Direct Democracy*.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe] ADDE was closed down in 2016 after an auditors' inquiry found misspending of EU funds.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe] The party was legally dissolved on 24 May 2017.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-for-europe-of-the-nations] The **Alliance for Europe of the Nations** was a European political party that gathered conservative and national-conservative political parties from across the continent.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-for-europe-of-the-nations] The AEN was founded in 2002, designed to complement the existing Union for Europe of the Nations group in the European Parliament.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-for-europe-of-the-nations] Moves towards establishing standardised funding block grants for European political parties were at this point well afoot, and the parties affiliated with UEN required a corresponding organisation to take advantage of them.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-for-europe-of-the-nations] Almost immediately upon its founding, the AEN began to decline in terms of membership and influence.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-for-europe-of-the-nations] At its first meeting, participants included the Czech Civic Democratic Party, Portuguese CDS-PP, Israeli Likud, Irish Fianna Fáil, Italian National Alliance and the Greek Popular Orthodox Rally, all of which later left the organisation.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-for-europe-of-the-nations] The AEN had a broadly national-conservative political line, but many members were uncomfortable with this.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-for-europe-of-the-nations] There was a strong movement for the centrist Fianna Fáil to leave AEN and join the European Liberal Democrat and Reform Party, which it did on 17 April 2009.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-for-europe-of-the-nations] After those realignments, there were too few AEN member parties left to retain its EU-funded status as a European political party.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] The **Alliance for Peace and Freedom** (**APF**) is a far-right European political alliance and former European political party founded on 4 February 2015.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] The main member parties were involved in the defunct **European National Front**.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] The alliance wishes to establish a network of nationalist movements across Europe that will cooperate to strengthen their shared ideals.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] It cooperates and supports other nationalist groups across Europe that are not members, these include former party members Golden Dawn, Tricolour Flame, Alternative for Sweden and the ELAM.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] The alliance is described as neo-Nazi by several newspapers, and neo-fascist by others.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] The group works for "a Europe of sovereign nations in which the independent states work together on a confederated basis", and for the perennity and the safeguarding of ancestral European traditions such as the Christian tradition.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] The Europa Terra Nostra is the official European political foundation of the APF.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] The ETN was founded 3 July 2015 in Berlin where it continues to operate as the official think-tank of the APF and serves as the European framework for national foundations/think-tanks recognised by APF member-parties.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] The APF works to co-ordinate European nationalist parties across the continent.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] It helped establish the Italy for the Italians coalition composed of APF member New Force along with Tricolour Flame.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] In 2017 the APF aided in the formation of the National Identity Bloc in Europe coalition, APF members, United Romania Party and Noua Dreaptă joined forces with the Greater Romania Party.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] In 2019 The APF played a part in forming the ADÑ Identidad Española coalition, composed of APF member National Democracy, FE-JONS, Spanish Alternative and La Falange.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] The party also maintains contacts with the former leader of the National Front, Jean-Marie Le Pen, who was expelled from his party in 2015.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] He joined the group in March 2018 as an Honorary Chairman and held this position until his death in January 2025.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] The APF maintains contacts with conservative circles in Russia with the group being invited to conferences hosted by the Kremlin.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] The party supports Vladimir Putin and United Russia's leadership of Russia, especially in the Russo-Ukrainian War and Syrian Civil War.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] The party is supportive of Alexander Lukashenko and maintains contacts with the Liberal Democratic Party of Belarus.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] The APF strongly supports Serbian nationalists and is opposed to international recognition of Kosovo, it has worked in the past with the Serbian Radical Party.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] On 26 September 2021, the APF held a conference in Belgrade hosted by the Serbian Right.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] It maintained friendly relations with the Syrian Arab Socialist Ba'ath Party government with deputy chairman, Nick Griffin being invited to Syria by Bashar al-Assad multiple times as an ambassador.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] Meetings between the party and the Syrian Social Nationalist Party have been held with the AFP publicly supporting the SSNP.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] The group maintains contacts with Hezbollah and has hosted at least one meeting with Hezbollah leaders.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] Michel Aoun, then president of Lebanon, received a delegation of the APF in 2018 and in 2019, and the group claims to have been in regular contact with him and his party.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-of-european-national-movements] The **Alliance of European National Movements** (**AENM**) was a European political party that was formed in Budapest on 24 October 2009 by a number of ultranationalist and far-right parties from countries in Europe.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-of-european-national-movements] AENM's founding members were Jobbik (the alliance was established during their sixth party congress), France's National Front, Italy's Tricolour Flame, Sweden's National Democrats and Belgium's National Front.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-of-european-national-movements] At the end of 2011, the National Front withdrew from AENM and joined the European Alliance for Freedom (EAF).
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-of-european-national-movements] In 2014, the All-Ukrainian Union "Freedom" terminated its observer status in the AENM, due to many members of the bloc showing support for Russia in the Russo-Ukrainian war.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-of-european-national-movements] In February 2016, Jobbik cut all of its affiliation with AENM, and the president of AENM Béla Kovács left Jobbik.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-of-european-national-movements] In November 2009, the British National Party claimed that AENM had been extended to nine parties, but this information was not confirmed by AENM President Bruno Gollnisch in 2012.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-of-european-national-movements] At a press conference held in Strasbourg on 16 June 2010, the political leadership of AENM was confirmed as follows: President Bruno Gollnisch, Vice President Nick Griffin, Treasurer Béla Kovács and Secretary General Valerio Cignetti.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-of-european-national-movements] At the end of 2011 the National Front withdrew from AENM and joined the European Alliance for Freedom.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-of-european-national-movements] However, Gollnisch and Jean-Marie Le Pen maintained their position in the organisation.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-of-european-national-movements] In October 2013, Marine Le Pen requested that Gollnisch and Jean-Marie Le Pen leave their positions in the AENM in order to join the more moderate EAF and so unify the French National Front under the EAF banner.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-of-european-national-movements] Marine Le Pen has tried to "de-demonize" the party, i.e. to give it a more acceptable image.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-of-european-national-movements] Cooperation with the openly racist and antisemitic parties present in AENM was seen as contradictory to these aims.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-of-european-national-movements] On November 7, the two declared they have followed the request and left AENM.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-of-european-national-movements] This also meant the end of Gollnisch's term as the AENM's chairman, a place occupied by Béla Kovács since January 2014.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-of-european-national-movements] In the spring of 2013, Svoboda lost its observer status after a conflict with other member groups over its policies towards ethnic minorities in the West of Ukraine.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-of-european-national-movements] Béla Kovács, leader of the alliance, had served as an observer at the 2014 Donbass parliamentary election.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-of-european-national-movements] In 2014, there were accusations against Chairman Kovács that he or his wife were working for the Russian intelligence service.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-of-european-national-movements] In 2015 the European Parliament lifted Kovács immunity.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-of-european-national-movements] In September 2020, he was cleared of the charge of espionage.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-of-european-national-movements] However, he had worked with the Russian secret service SVR RF, but mostly in the form of influencing, with the aim to promote Russian interests through the AEMN.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-of-european-national-movements] Kovács was sentenced to one and a half years imprisonment for fraud and falsification of documents to the detriment of the European Parliament.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-of-european-national-movements] The party did not apply for registration with the newly established Authority for European Political Parties and European Political Foundations (APPF), which was required from 2017, in good time.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-of-european-national-movements] An application by the party foundation ITE was rejected by the APPF, as the AEMN was not registered itself at that time.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-of-european-national-movements] Subsequently, the AEMN's application for funding for 2018 was rejected accordingly.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-of-european-national-movements] Finally, the AEMN was registered as a European political party on 12 January 2018.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-of-european-national-movements] At the end of 2018, the AENM was removed from the register again.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-of-european-national-movements] The background was a change in the registration rules, according to which European parties had to submit member parties (with parliamentarians) from seven EU member states in the register.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-of-european-national-movements] This put an end to the previous practice of AENM registering individual parliamentarians from national parties who did not belong to AENM but to other European parties.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-of-european-national-movements] For example, parliamentarians from the Front National had regularly provided signatures for the AENM, the APF and the MENL – to which the FN belongs.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-of-european-national-movements] For the 2019 European Parliament election, AEMN chairman Kovacs provided the necessary signature of support for the candidacy of the Italian party CasaPound Italia.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-of-european-national-movements] None of the parties in the AEMN's environment was able to win mandates in the election.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-of-european-national-movements] After the election, the party was no longer active.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-of-european-national-movements] For the 2024 European Parliament election in Italy, Royal Italy submitted a symbol with the text "Alleanza europea dei movimenti nazionali" at the top.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-of-european-national-movements] In 2022, Royal Italy ran with United Right who made a deal with CasaPound in 2019.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe] The **Alliance of Independent Democrats in Europe** (AIDE) (**Alliance des Démocrates Indépendants en Europe** (ADIE) in French) was a Eurosceptic, nationalist European political party.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe] AIDE was created on 28 October 2005 in the Rhône prefecture.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe] AIDE described itself as the centre-right faction of the eurosceptic IND/DEM group, with the EUDemocrats, the United Kingdom Independence Party and the European Christian Political Movement comprising the other factions of that group.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe] As of January 2007, the group operated a limited French-language website.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe] The group's website implied the existence of British, Czech, French, Greek, Irish, Italian and Polish delegations and identified Movement for France (MpF) MEP Patrick Louis as the president of AIDE.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe] AIDE was dissolved with effect from 31 December 2008 and was defunded in the February 2009 meeting of the Bureau of the European Parliament.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] The **Alliance of Liberals and Democrats for Europe Party** (**ALDE Party**) is a liberal European political party composed of national parties from across Europe, mainly active in the European Union.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] The ALDE Party is affiliated with Liberal International and a recognised European political party, incorporated as a non-profit association under Belgian law.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] It was founded on 26 March 1976 in Stuttgart as a confederation of national political parties under the name "Federation of Liberal and Democrat Parties in Europe" and renamed "European Liberals and Democrats" (ELD) in 1977 and "European Liberal Democrats and Reformists" (ELDR) in 1986.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] On 30 April 2004, the ELDR was reformed as an official European party, the "European Liberal Democrat and Reform Party" (ELDR Party).
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] Prior to the 2004 European election, the European party had been represented through its own group, the European Liberal Democrat and Reform Party Group (ELDR) Group.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] In June 2019, the ALDE group was succeeded by Renew Europe.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] As of 2024, ALDE Party is represented in European Union institutions, with 51 MEPs and five members of the European Commission.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] Of the 27 EU member states, there are two with ALDE-affiliated Prime Ministers: Kristen Michal (Estonian Reform Party) in Estonia and Alexander De Croo (Open VLD) in Belgium.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] ALDE Party members are also in governments in ten other EU member states: Cyprus, France, Denmark, Finland, Sweden, Ireland, Luxembourg, Lithuania, Germany and the Netherlands.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] Charles Michel, former Belgian prime minister, was the president of the European Council until December 2024.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] ALDE's think tank is the European Liberal Forum, led by Jan-Christoph Oetjen MEP, and gathers 46 member organisations.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] The youth wing of ALDE is the European Liberal Youth (LYMEC), which is predominantly based upon youth and student liberal organisations but contains also a small number of individual members.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] In 2011, ALDE Party became the first pan-European party to create the status of individual membership.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] Since then, between 1000 and close to 3000 members (the numbers fluctuate annually) maintained direct membership in the ALDE Party from several EU countries.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] Over 40 coordinators mobilised liberal ideas, initiatives and expertise across the continent under the leadership of the steering committee, which was first chaired by Julie Cantalou.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] The ALDE Party took a step further in the direction of becoming a truly pan-European party when granting voting rights to individual members' delegates at the Party Congress.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] Individual membership was eventually discontinued in 2023.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] In 2025, the Alliance was declared an undesirable organization in Russia.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] Pan-European liberalism has a long history dating back to the foundation of Liberal International in April 1947.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] On 26 March 1976, the Federation of Liberal and Democrat Parties in Europe was established in Stuttgart.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] The founding parties of the federation were the Free Democratic Party of Germany, Radical Party of France, Venstre of Denmark, Italian Liberal Party, Dutch People's Party for Freedom and Democracy and Democratic Party of Luxembourg.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] Observer members joining later in 1976 were the Danish Social Liberal Party, French Radical Party of the Left and Independent Republicans, British Liberal Party, and Italian Republican Party.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] In 1977, the federation was renamed European Liberals and Democrats, in 1986, European Liberal Democrats and Reformists.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] On 10 November 2012, the ELDR Party adopted the name of the alliance between the two parties, to match the parliamentary group and the alliance.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] On 12 June 2019, the ALDE group was succeeded by a new enlarged group, Renew Europe, which primarily consists of ALDE and EDP member parties and France's La République En Marche!
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] As a registered European political party, ALDE is entitled to European public funding, which it has received continuously since 2004.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] Below is the evolution of European public funding received by ALDE.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] In line with the Regulation on European political parties and European political foundations, ALDE also raises private funds to co-finance its activities.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] As of 2025, European parties must raise at least 10% of their reimbursable expenditure from private sources, while the rest can be covered using European public funding.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] Below is the evolution of contributions and donations received by the ALDE.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] As of January 2026 ALDE party had 55 full member and ten affiliated parties from EU and non-EU countries.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] Only delegates from full members of the ALDE Party and its youth wing LYMEC, together with the delegates of the ALDE Party Supporters and ALDE Party Bureau members, are permitted to vote at the ALDE Congress and Council.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] Affiliated member parties have non-voting delegates.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] ALDE also includes a number of individual members.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] For many years, ALDE had the largest number of individual members of all European parties; however, this membership was discontinued with only one individual member remaining as of 2024.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] As most other European parties, it has not sought to develop mass individual membership.
[src:alliance-for-peace-and-freedom/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] Below is the evolution of individual membership of ALDE since 2019.
